)^{\sharp}.$$ \end{enumerate} \end{lemma}  egin{proof} We will reduce to universal properties of the terms of the isomorphisms. For $\sh \in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$, we have  egin{align*} & \Hom^{\Box}_{S}((\sff\otimes^{\Box,{m psh}}\sg)^{\sharp},\sh)\simeq \Hom_{m psh}(\sff \otimes^{\Box,{m psh}}\sg,\sh)\simeq \Hom_{m psh}(\sff,\Hhom_{S^{m top}}(\sg,\sh))\ & \simeq \Hom_{m psh}(\sff^\sharp,\Hhom_{S^{m top}}(\sg,\sh))\simeq \Hom_{m psh}(\sff^\sharp\otimes^{\Box,{m psh}}\sg,\sh). \end{align*} Here we wrote $\Hom_{m psh}(-,-) $ for the sets of morphisms in ${m PSh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$. Repeating this computation with $\sg$ in place of $\sff$ yields claim (1) of the lemma. The proof of the second claim of the lemma is similar. \end{proof} The solid tensor product of sheaves inherits many properties from the solid tensor product of modules. In particular, it commutes with all colimits (since the sheafification functor does). The internal $\Hom$, $\Hhom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff,\sg)$, can be defined as a presheaf by $$ \{Y\mapsto \uHom^{\Box}_{Y}(\sff_Y,\sg_Y)\in {m Solid}\},\quad Y\in S_{\proeet}. $$ It is actually a sheaf by \cite[Prop. 2.2.14]{Schn}. Moreover, the image of the sheaf $\Hhom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff,\sg)$ by the embedding functor ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})\hookrightarrow {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m CondAb})$ is the sheaf $\Hhom_{S^{m top}}(\sff,\sg)$. We have the usual adjointness property:  egin{lemma}\label{adj1}If $\sff_1,\sff_2,\sff_3\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$, there is a canonical functorial isomorphism in ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$ $$ \Hhom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff_1\otimes^{\Box}\sff_2,\sff_3)\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \Hhom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff_1,\Hhom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff_2,\sff_3)). $$ In particular, we have a canonical functorial isomorphism in ${m Solid}$ $$ \Hom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff_1\otimes^{\Box}\sff_2,\sff_3)\simeq \Hom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff_1,\Hhom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff_2,\sff_3)). $$ \end{lemma}  egin{proof} This can be checked in $ {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m CondAb})$, where it is known. \end{proof} ($ ullet$) {\em Sheaves of solid $\underline{\Q}_p$-modules.} Let ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ denote the subcategory of ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$ of $\underline{\Q}_{p}$-modules.  egin{lemma}\label{Gro1} The category ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ is a Grothendieck abelian category. \end{lemma}  egin{proof} We need to check that the category ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ admits a generator and small colimits such that small filtered colimits are exact. But the colimits can be inherited from ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$ and they have the required properties (use the fact that the solid tensor product of solid abelian sheaves commutes with direct sums). Moreover, if $X$ is a generator of ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$ then $\underline{\Q}_p\otimes^{\Box}X$ is a generator of ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ as easily follows, again, from the fact that the solid tensor product of solid abelian sheaves commutes with direct sums. This finishes our argument. \end{proof} The categories of $\Q_p(Y)_{\Box}$-modules, $ Y\in S_{\proeet}$, being closed symmetric monoidal, the category ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ is equipped with tensor product and internal $\Hom$: For $\sff,\sg\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box}})$, their tensor product $\sff\otimes^{\Box}_{\underline{\Q}_p}\sg$ is defined by sheafifying the presheaf tensor product $$ \{Y\mapsto \sff(Y)\otimes^{\Box}_{\underline{\Q}_{p}(Y)}\sg(Y)\},\quad Y\in S_{\proeet}. $$ We have an analog of Lemma ef{tensor} in this setting. The internal $\Hom$, $\Hhom^{\Box}_{S,\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff,\sg)$, can be defined as a presheaf by $$ \{Y\mapsto \uHom^{\Box}_{Y, \underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff_Y,\sg_Y)\in {m Mod}_{\Q_p(Y)}^{m solid}\},\quad Y\in S_{\proeet}, $$ where we set  egin{equation}\label{coend1b} \uHom^{\Box}_{Y,\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff_Y,\sg_Y) :=\ker\Big(\prod_{Y_1	o Y}\uHom^{\Box}_{\Q_p(Y_1)}(\sff(Y_1),\sg(Y_1))	o \prod_{Y_2	o Y_1}\uHom^{\Box}_{\Q_p(Y_1)}(\sff(Y_1),\sg(Y_2))\Big). \end{equation} It is actually a sheaf (compare with the condensed definition). Moreover, the image of the sheaf $\Hhom^{\Box}_{S,\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff,\sg)$ by the forgetful functor ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})	o {m Sh}(S^{m top}_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p})$ is the sheaf $\Hhom_{S^{m top},\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff,\sg)$. In particular, the forgetful functor ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})	o {m Sh}(S^{m top}_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p})$ is (topologically) fully faithful. We have the usual adjointness property:  egin{lemma}\label{kaczka20} If $\sff_1,\sff_2,\sff_3\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$, there is a canonical functorial isomorphism in ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ $$ \Hhom^{\Box}_{S,\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff_1\otimes^{\Box}_{\underline{\Q}_p}\sff_2, \sff_3)\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \Hhom^{\Box}_{S,\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff_1,\Hhom^{\Box}_{S,\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff_2, \sff_3)). $$ In particular, we have a canonical functorial isomorphism in ${m Mod}^{m solid}_{\Q_p(S)}$ $$ \uHom^{\Box}_{S,\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff_1\otimes^{\Box}_{\underline{\Q}_p}\sff_2, \sff_3)\simeq \uHom^{\Box}_{S,\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff_1,\Hhom^{\Box}_{S,\underline{\Q}_{p}}(\sff_2, \sff_3)). $$ \end{lemma}  egin{proof}Reduce to the condensed adjointness as in the proof of Lemma ef{adj1}. \end{proof} The category $ {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ is generated by the set  egin{equation}\label{koczkodan3} \{\underline{\Q_p}[h^{\delta}_Y]\otimes^{\Box}_{\Z}\Z[T]\}, \quad Y\in {m Perf}_S, T - \mbox{ profinite set}. \end{equation} And we have an analog of Lemma ef{koczkodan2} in this setting. \vskip3mm ($ ullet$) {\em Derived picture.} Again, we have an analogous derived picture. We start with the category $\sd(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$. Since ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$ is a Grothendieck abelian category, the internal $\Hom$, $\R\Hhom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff,\sg)$, for $\sff,\sg\in \sd(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$, is defined using the existence of $K$-injective resolutions (which is a classical result, see \cite{Ser}, \cite[Tag 079I]{Stck}). The existence of $K$-flat resolutions, which follows from the existence of flat generators from ef{koczkodan4}, yields the derived tensor product $\sff\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}\sg$, for $\sff, \sg\in \sd(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$. By the usual argument (\cite[Tag 08J9]{Stck}), the derived tensor product is the left (interior) adjoint to the derived interior $\Hom$. We pass now to the category $\sd(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$. The existence of $K$-injective resolutions follows from the fact that the category ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ is Grothendieck abelian (see Lemma ef{Gro1}). The existence of $K$-flat resolutions follows from the existence of flat generators of ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ (see \eqref{koczkodan3}). Hence we have the derived tensor product $\sff\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\underline{\Q}_p}\sg$, for $\sff, \sg\in\sd(S_{\proeet},{\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box}})$, the internal $\Hom$, $\R\Hhom^{\Box}_{S,\underline{\Q}_p}(\sff,\sg)$, which are (internal) adjoints to each other. \subsubsection{Constant sheaves and monoidal structures} Let $W\in K_{\Box}$ be a flat module and let ootnote{The definition and properties of the category ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet}, K_{\Box})$ is analogous to those of the category $ {m Sh}(S_{\proeet}, \Q_{p,\Box})$.} $\sff\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet}, K_{\Box})$. We define sheaves $ W\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{K}\sff, W\otimes^{\Box}_{K}\sff$ as presheaves by setting  egin{align*} W\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{K}\sff:=\{Y\mapsto W\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{K}\sff(Y)\},\ W\otimes^{\Box}_{K}\sff:=\{Y\mapsto W\otimes^{\Box}_{K}\sff(Y)\}. \end{align*} These are sheaves because $W$ is a flat module. We will need the following computations:  egin{lemma}\label{form23} Let $W\in \Q_{p,\Box}$ be a Fr'echet or of compact type. Let $\sff\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet}, \underline{\Q}_{p,\Box} )$.  egin{enumerate} \item There is a canonical quasi-isomorphism in $\sd(S_{\proeet},\Q_{p,\Box})$  egin{equation}\label{form11-1} W\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\Q_{p}}\sff\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \underline{W}\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\Q_{p}}\sff. \end{equation} \item There is a natural isomorphism in $\Q_{p,\Box}$ $$\uHom^{\Box}_{S,\Q_p}(\underline{W} ,\sff) \stackrel{\sim}{	o} \uHom^{\Box}_{ \Q_p} (W,\sff(S)).$$ \item There is a natural quasi-isomorphism in $\sd(\Q_{p,\Box})$ $$\R\uHom^{\Box}_{S,\Q_p}(\underline{W},\sff) \simeq \R\uHom_{\Q_{p,\Box}} (W,\R\Gamma(S^{m top}_{\proeet},\sff)). $$ \item If $W$ is of compact type then there is a natural quasi-isomorphism in $\sd(\Q_{p,\Box})$ $$\R\uHom^{\Box}_{S,\Q_p}(\underline{W},\sff) \simeq W^*\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\Q_p}\R\Gamma(S^{m top}_{\proeet},\sff). $$ \end{enumerate} \end{lemma}  egin{proof} We start with the first claim. As presheaves both sides of \eqref{form11-1} are given by  egin{align*} \{Y\mapsto W\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\Q_{p}}\sff(Y)\},\quad \{Y\mapsto \underline{W}(Y)\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\Q_{p}(Y)}\sff(Y)\}, \end{align*} respectively. For $Y$ strictly totally disconnected, we compute  egin{align*} \underline{W}(Y)\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\Q_{p}(Y)}\sff(Y) & =\scc(\pi_0(Y),W)\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\Q_{p}(Y)}\sff(Y)\simeq W{\otimes}^{{\Box}}_{\Q_{p}}\scc(\pi_0(Y),\Q_p)\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\Q_{p}(Y)}\sff(Y)\ & \simeq W\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}_{\Q_{p}}\sff(Y) \end{align*} Here, the second quasi-isomorphism holds by \cite[Cor. 10.5.4]{PGS}. Our claim follows. For the second claim, we use the end description  egin{align*} \uHom^{\Box}_{S,\Q_p}(\underline{W} ,\sff) & \stackrel{\sim}{	o} \uHom^{\Box}_{S,\Q_p}({W} \otimes^{\Box}_{\Q_{p}}\underline{\Q}_p,\sff) = \int_{Y} \uHom_{\Q_p(Y)}(W\otimes^{\Box}_{\Q_{p}}\Q_p(Y) ,\sff(Y))\ & \simeq \int_{Y} \uHom_{\Q_p}(W ,\sff(Y))\simeq \uHom_{\Q_p}(W ,\int_{Y} \sff(Y))\simeq \uHom_{\Q_p} (W,\sff(S)). \end{align*} Here, the first isomorphism follows from the first claim of the lemma. The last two claims of the lemma follow from the first two ones by applying them to an injective resolution of $\sff$. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Condensed versus solid sheaves} The following result is a sheaf version of Proposition ef{nyear1}.  egin{proposition}\label{nyear1a}  egin{enumerate} \item The forgetful functor  egin{equation}\label{form1a} {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})	o {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m CondAb}) \end{equation} is (topologically) fully faithful. The essential image is stable under all limits, colimits, and extensions. Moreover, the inclusion \eqref{form1a} admits a (topological) left adjoint, the solidification functor,  egin{equation} \label{form11a} {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m CondAb})	o {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Solid}): \quad \sff \mapsto \sff^{\Box}, \end{equation} which preserves all colimits and is symmetric monoidal. We have analogous claims for the forgetful functor ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet},\Q_{p,\Box}) 	o {m Sh}(S^{m top}_{\proeet},\Q_p)$. \item The forgetful functor  egin{equation}\label{form2a} \sd(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})	o \sd(S_{\proeet},{m CondAb}) \end{equation} is (topologically) fully faithful. It preserves all limits and colimits. \item The functor \eqref{form2a} admits a left adjoint $$\sff \mapsto \sff^{\LL_{\Box}}: \sd(S_{\proeet},{m CondAb}) 	o \sd(S_{\proeet},{m Solid}), $$ which is the (topological) left derived functor of the solidification functor $(-)^{\Box}$. It is symmetric monoidal. We have analogous claims for the forgetful functor $\sd(S_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})	o \sd(S^{m top}_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p})$. \item For $\sff_1, \sff_2 \in \sd(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$, the natural map $$\R{\Hhom}^{\Box}_{S}(\sff_1,\sff_2) 	o \R{\Hhom}_{S^{m top}}(\sff_1,\sff_2)$$ is a quasi-isomorphism. We have an analogous claim for the $\underline{\Q}_p$-sheaves. \end{enumerate} \end{proposition}  egin{proof} We start with the first claim. The fully-faitfulness was shown above, in Section ef{solid1} (see Lemma ef{solidification1}). Limits of solid sheaves in the condensed setting are solid because this is true for presheaves; for colimits -- this holds on the level of presheaves and condensed sheafification is compatible with solid sheafification. For extensions: If $0	o \sff_1	o \sff_2	o \sff_3	o 0 $ is an extension of condensed sheaves such that $\sff_1,\sff_3$ are solid then, on every $Y\in S_{\proeet}$, we have an exact sequence in ${m CondAb}$ $$ 0	o \sff_1(Y)	o \sff_2(Y)	o \sff_3(Y)\stackrel{f}{	o} H^1_{\proeet}(Y,\sff_1). $$ The cohomology group $H^1_{\proeet}(Y,\sff_1)$ is solid (because so is $\sff_1$), hence so is the kernel of the map~$f$. Thus, by Proposition ef{nyear1}, $\sff_2(Y)$ is solid, as wanted. The claim about solidification follows from Lemma ef{solidification1}, Lemma ef{tensor}, and Proposition ef{nyear1}. We turn now to the second claim of the proposition. For fully-faitfulness, for $\sff,\sg\in \sd(S_{\proeet},{m Solid})$, we need to show that the canonical map $$ \R\uHom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff,\sg ) 	o \R\uHom_{S^{m top}}(\sff,\sg ) $$ is a quasi-isomorphism. We will need the following fact:  egin{lemma}\label{paris20} If $W$ is a prodiscrete condensed set (i.e. a cofiltered limit of discrete condensed sets) then $\Z[W]^{\LL_{\Box}}\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \Z[W]^{\Box}$. Similalry with $\underline{\Q}_p(S)$-coefficients, for $S\in {m Perf}_C$. \end{lemma}  egin{proof} Recall that every prodiscrete set can be written as a filtered colimit of profinite sets. So let us write $W=\colim_iT_i$, a filtered colimit of profinite sets. We have $$ \Z[W]^{\LL_{\Box}}=\Z[\colim_iT_i]^{\LL_{\Box}}\simeq(\colim_i\Z[T_i])^{\LL_{\Box}}\simeq \colim_i\Z[T_i]^{\LL_{\Box}}\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \colim_i\Z[T_i]^{\Box}\simeq \Z[W]^{\Box}, $$ which is what we wanted. The $\Q_p$-case follows from the fact that $\Z[T]$ is a flat solid abelian group. \end{proof} This implies that if we take a resolution of $\sff$ in ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet}, {m CondAb})$ $$ \cdots 	o P_1	o P_0	o \sff	o 0, $$ where $P_j=\oplus_j(\Z[h^{\delta}_{Y_j}]\otimes\Z[T_j])$ for a w-contractible $Y_j$ over $S$, an extremally diconnected $T_j$, the solidification $$ \cdots 	o P_1^{\Box}	o P_0^{\Box}	o \sff	o 0 $$ is also exact. Indeed, it suffices to show that $$ \cdots 	o P_1(X)^{\Box}	o P_0(X)^{\Box}	o \sff(X)^{\Box}	o 0, $$ is exact for a w-contractible $X$ over $S$. But this follows from the quasi-isomorphism $\sff(X)^{\LL_{\Box}}\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \sff(X)^{\Box}$, since $\sff(X)$ is solid, and Lemma ef{paris20}. Using that the $P_i$'s above are projective in ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet}, {m CondAb})$ and their solidifications are projective in ${m Sh}(S_{\proeet}, {m Solid})$, the fully faithfulness claim is reduced to the fact that the map  egin{equation}\label{koczkodan5} \Hom^{\Box}_{S}(\Z[h^{\delta}_Y]\otimes^{\Box}\Z[T],\sg ) 	o \Hom_{S^{m top}}(\Z[h^{\delta}_Y]\otimes\Z[T],\sg ) \end{equation} is an isomorphism for a w-contractible $Y$ over $S$, an extremally diconnected $T$, and a solid sheaf $\sg$. But this follows from the first claim of the proposition. The topological version can be derived by the same argument applied to the tensor products $\sff\otimes^{\Box}\Z[T]$'s. This also proves the fourth claim of the proposition. The statement about colimits in claim (2) follows by evaluating sheaves on w-contractible perfectoids. For limits -- we use the fact that in both categories we have, for $Y$ over $S$ w-contractible, we have $(\R\lim_{i\in I}\sff_i)(Y)\simeq \R\lim_{i\in I}\sff_i(Y)$ and, by Proposition ef{nyear1}, the latter limits are the same in the solid and condensed categories. For claim (3), since we have enough projectives, the left derived functor $(-)^{\LL_{\Box}}$ of $(-)^{\Box}$ exists and it remains to show that it is the left adjoint of the map \eqref{form1a}. But this can be checked on $\uHom$'s and for projectives $\Z[h^{\delta}_{Y}]\otimes\Z[T]$ as in \eqref{koczkodan5} and then we can use claim (1). This also implies inner left adjointness, which, in turn, implies compatibility with monoidal structures via the following computation: We want to show that, for $\sff_1, \sff_2\in \sd(S_{\proeet},{m CondAb})$, we have  egin{equation}\label{chicago1} ( \sff_1\otimes^{\LL}\sff_2)^{\LL_{\Box}}\simeq \sff_1^{\LL_{\Box}}\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}\sff_2^{\LL_{\Box}} \end{equation} in $\sd(S_{\proeet}, {m Solid})$. But, for $\sg\in\sd(S_{\proeet}, {m Solid})$, by the already proven adjointness properties and claim (4) of our proposition, we have the following quasi-isomorphims  egin{align*} \R\Hom^{\Box}_{S}((\sff_1\otimes^{\LL}\sff_2)^{\LL_{\Box}},\sg) & \simeq \R\Hom_{S^{m top}}(\sff_1\otimes^{\LL}\sff_2,\sg)\simeq \R\Hom_{S^{m top}}(\sff_1,\R\Hhom_{S^{m top}}(\sff_2,\sg))\ & \stackrel{\sim}{\leftarrow} \R\Hom_{S^{m top}}(\sff_1,\R\Hhom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff^{\LL_{\Box}}_2,\sg)) \simeq \R\Hom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff^{\LL_{\Box}}_1, \R\Hhom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff^{\LL_{\Box}}_2,\sg)) \ & \simeq \R\Hom^{\Box}_{S}(\sff^{\LL_{\Box}}_1\otimes^{\LL_{\Box}}\sff^{\LL_{\Box}}_2,\sg), \end{align*} as wanted. Claim (3) for $\underline{\Q}_p$-coefficients follows by the same argument as in the abelian case. \end{proof}  egin{remark} Recall that sheaves of $\underline{\Q}_p$-modules on ${m Spa}(C)_{\proeet}$ are called Vector Spaces (${m VS}$ for short). Following this, we will call sheaves from ${m Sh}({m Spa}(C)_{\proeet},\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ {\em Naive Topological Vector Spaces} (${m NTVS}$ for short). \end{remark} \subsubsection{'Etale Naive Topological Vector Spaces} The constructions from Section ef{defnaive} and Section ef{naive52} have 'etale versions though one needs to be a bit careful so that all of them go through. Let $S$ be a strictly totally disconnected affinoid perfectoid over $C$. Denote by ${m sPerf}_S$ the category of strictly totally disconnected affinoid perfectoid spaces over $S$. Proceeding as in Section ef{naive-521} we can define the topological 'etale site $S^{m top}_{\eet}$ based on the category ${m sPerf}_S$ equipped with 'etale topology. The constructions from Section ef{defnaive} and Section ef{naive52} go through with two exceptions: we do not have the map $\eta$ from Section ef{naive-521} and in Lemma ef{koczkodan2} we can take all $Y$'s. In fact, later on, we will go even further and often drop the topology altogether (but still work with the category ${m sPerf}_S$). \section{Topological Vector Spaces} We pass now to our main object of study: the categories of topologically enriched presheaves. We start with the definition and properties of topology on mapping spaces between perfectoid affinoids over $C$. Then we define topologically enriched presheaves with values in condensed and solid abelian groups, discuss examples and the Enriched Yoneda Lemma. After that we prove that topologically enriched presheaves form Grothendieck abelian categories, study their $\infty$-derived categories, the solidification functors, and monoidal structures. Finally, we extend all of this to the categories of $\underline{\Q}_p$-modules. \subsection{Topologically enriched presheaves}\label{ias1} Many of the topological presheaves we will be working with will be canonically enriched.  egin{remark} The main technical tool that we need that convinced us to use topologically enriched presheaves is the enriched Yoneda Lemma that is needed in the proof of Theorem ef{duck1} and Theorem ef{lebrasII} (used to relate topological $\R\Hom$'s to the algebraic ones and the ones for perfect complexes on the Fargues-Fontaine curve). The consideration of topologically enriched presheaves is not new:  egin{enumerate} \item It appears implicitly in the original definition of Banach-Colmez spaces in \cite{CF} (Banach-Colmez spaces are presheaves valued in Banach spaces and are topologically enriched) and also explicitly ootnote{Though at the time of writing \cite{CN5} the authors were not aware that the extra continuity property they have imposed amounts to the notion of enrichment in category theory.} in the definition of ${m qBC}$'s in \cite{CN5}. \item Topologically enriched functors in the context of the theory of Banach spaces were studied for a while: see, for example, \cite{HP}, \cite{Pel}. They are called "strong functors" there. More generally, the papers \cite{Cas1}, \cite{Cas2} survey the categorical approach to the theory of Banach spaces. \end{enumerate} \end{remark} Our main references for enriched categories and enriched functors are \cite{Kelly}, \cite{GM}, \cite[App. C]{HM}. \subsubsection{Topologized mapping space} Let $S\in {m Perf}_C$. We will enrich the category ${m Perf}_S$ in ${m Cond}$. For $Y_1, Y_2\in{m Perf}_S$, we set: $$ \uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2): \{T\mapsto \Hom_S(Y_1	imes T,Y_2)\}. $$ For every $Y\in {m Perf}_S$, the {\em identity map} $i_X:\{*\}	o \uHom_S(Y,Y)$ sends $\{*\}$ to ${m Id}$. For every triple $Y_1,Y_2,Y_3\in {m Perf}_S$, the {\em composition} map $$ \uHom_S(Y_2,Y_3)\otimes \uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)	o \uHom_S(Y_1,Y_3) $$ is defined by compatible compositions, for profinite sets $T$, $$ \Hom_S(Y_2	imes T,Y_3)\otimes \Hom_S(Y_1	imes T,Y_2)	o \Hom_S(Y_1	imes T,Y_3), $$ which send the pair $(f_2,f_1)$ to the composition $$ f_2f_1:\quad Y_1	imes T\lomapr{{m Id}	imes \Delta} Y_1	imes T	imes T\lomapr{f_1	imes{m Id} }Y_2	imes T\lomapr{f_2}Y_3. $$ The associativity and unit axioms (see \cite[(1.3), (1.4)]{Kelly}) are easily checked to hold.  egin{lemma}\label{prodiscrete} The condensed set $ \uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)$ is prodiscrete. \end{lemma}  egin{proof} Set $R^+_1:= R^+_{Y_1}, R^+_2:= R^+_{Y_2}, R^+_S:= R^+_{S}$. These are prodiscrete sets. We claim that there is an isomorphism of condensed sets $$ \uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)\simeq \underline{\Hom}_{\underline{R}^+_S}^{m Alg}(\underline{R}^+_2, \underline{R}^+_1), $$ where the second $\Hom$ is taken in $\underline{R}^+_S$-algebras. To see this we start with showing that there is an isomorphism of condensed sets $$ \uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)\simeq \underline{\Hom_{R^+_S}^{m Alg}(R^+_2, R^+_1)}, $$ where $ \Hom_{R^+_S}^{m Alg}(R^+_2, R^+_1)$ is equipped with the compact-open topology. For that, we compute:  egin{align*} \Hom_S(Y_1	imes T,Y_2) & =\Hom_{R^+_S}^{m Alg}(R^+_2, R^+_1\wh{\otimes}\scc(T,\so_C))\simeq \Hom_{R^+_S}^{m Alg}(R^+_2, \scc(T,R^+_1))\ & \simeq \scc(T, \Hom_{R^+_S}^{m Alg}(R^+_2, R^+_1)), \end{align*} where the last isomorphism follows from the exponential law since $T, R^+_1, R^+_2$ are compactly generated (since they are colimits of profinite sets) and Hausdorff. By \cite[Prop. 4.2]{Sch19}, we have the natural isomorphism of condensed sets $$ \underline{\Hom}_{\underline{R}^+_S}^{m Alg}(\underline{R}^+_2, \underline{R}^+_1)\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \underline{\Hom_{R^+_S}^{m Alg}(R^+_2, R^+_1)}. $$ It suffices now to show that $\underline{\Hom}_{\underline{R}^+_S}^{m Alg}(\underline{R}^+_2, \underline{R}^+_1)$ is prodiscrete. But this is a closed condensed subset of $ \uHom_{\underline{\so}_C}(\underline{R}^+_2,\underline{R}^+_1)$ hence, by \cite{MO}, it suffices to show that $ \uHom_{\underline{\so}_C}(\underline{R}^+_2,\underline{R}^+_1)$ is prodiscrete. For that, we compute  egin{align*} \uHom_{\underline{\so}_C}(\underline{R}^+_2,\underline{R}^+_1) & \simeq \lim_n \uHom_{\underline{\so}_{C,n}}(\underline{R}^+_{2,n},\underline{R}^+_{1,n}) \simeq \lim_n \uHom_{\underline{\so}_{C,n}}(\colim_i\underline{R}^+_{2,n,i},\underline{R}^+_{1,n})\ & \simeq \lim_n \lim_i\uHom_{\underline{\so}_{C,n}}(\underline{R}^+_{2,n,i},\underline{R}^+_{1,n}), \end{align*} where $\underline{R}^+_{2,n,i}\subset \underline{R}^+_{2,n}$ are finitely generated $\underline{\so}_{C,n}$-modules. Getting what we wanted. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Topologically enriched presheaves} \label{warsz1} Let $\scc$ be a bicomplete, locally finitely presentable, closed symmetric monoidal category (for example, ${m Cond}$, ${m CondAb}$, ${m Solid}$). Such a category $\scc$ is canonically $\scc$-enriched ($\scc$-category, for short) and we assume that it is a ${m Cond}$-subcategory of ${m Cond}$. We will denote by $\Hom_{\scc}(-,-)$ and $\uHom_{\scc}(-,-)$ its $\Hom$-set and $\scc$-$\Hom$, respectively. We have $\uHom_{\scc}(-,-)(*)\simeq \Hom_{\scc}(-,-)$. If $\scc={m Cond}$ we will skip the subscripts. Let $S\in {m Perf}_C$. A $\scc$-{\em enriched presheaf} (or $\scc$-presheaf for short) $\sff: {m Perf}^{m op}_S 	o \scc$ consists of a function $$\sff: {m Perf}_S \mapsto {m Ob} \scc$$ together with, for $Y_1, Y_2\in{m Perf}_S$, a map of condensed sets  egin{equation}\label{str2} \underline{\sff}_{Y_1, Y_2}:\quad\uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)	o \uHom_{\scc}(\sff(Y_2),\sff(Y_1)) \end{equation} in a manner compatible with compositions and identities (see \cite[(1.5), (1.6)]{Kelly}). For $\scc$-presheaves $\sff, \sg$, a $\scc$-natural transformation $f: \sff	o \sg$ is a ${m Perf}_S$-indexed family of maps in $\scc$: $$ f_Y: \sff(Y)	o \sg(Y) $$ satisfying a $\scc$-naturality condition (see \cite[(1.7)]{Kelly}, \cite[(4.30)]{GM}): the following diagram commutes in ${m Cond}$ $$ \xymatrix{ \uHom_S(Y,Y_1)\ar[r]^-{\underline{\sff}_{Y,Y_1}} \ar[d]^-{\underline{\sg}_{Y,Y_1}} & \uHom_{\scc}(\sff(Y_1),\sff(Y))\ar[d]^{f_{*,Y}} \ \uHom_{\scc}(\sg(Y_1),\sg(Y)) \ar[r]^{f^*_{Y_1}} & \uHom_{\scc}(\sff(Y_1),\sg(Y)). } $$ We will write $\Hom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)$ for the set of $\scc$-natural transformations. We will denote the category of such presheaves by $\underline{m PSh}(S,\scc)_0$ and, in the case $\scc={m Cond}$, we will simply write $\underline{m PSh}(S)_0$.  egin{example} (1) The topological sheaves that come from $S_{\proeet}$ are canonically enriched:  egin{lemma}\label{enriched1}Let $\sff\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet})$. The sheaf $\pi_*\sff\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Cond})$ is canonically enriched. \end{lemma}  egin{proof} We need to define, compatible in $T$, maps  egin{equation}\label{maps1}\Hom_S(Y_1	imes T,Y_2)	o \Hom(\pi_*\sff(Y_2)	imes T,\pi_*\sff(Y_1))=\{T_1: \sff(Y_2	imes T_1)	imes \underline{T}(T_1)	o \sff(Y_1	imes T_1)\}. \end{equation} We induce them by the following transformation of maps over $S$ $$ (Y_1	imes T\stackrel{f}{	o} Y_2)	imes (T_1\stackrel{g}{	o} T)\mapsto (Y_1	imes T_1\stackrel{fg}{\longrightarrow} Y_2)\mapsto (Y_1	imes T_1\stackrel{(fg,{m Id})}{\longrightarrow} Y_2	imes T_1). $$ Clearly, evaluating \eqref{maps1} on $*$ yields the structure map \eqref{str1}. Commutativity of the composition and the identities diagrams \cite[(1.5), (1.6)]{Kelly} is easy (if tedious) to check. \end{proof} (2) Lemma ef{enriched1} combined with Example ef{ex1} yield that the sheaves $\Q_p, {\mathbb G}_a\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Cond})$ are canonically enriched and so are the period sheaves ${\mathbb B}^+_{\dr}/t^i$ and ${\mathbb B}_{\crr}^{+,\phi=p^i}$, $i\geq 0$. \end{example} \subsubsection{The ${m Cond}$-category of topologically enriched presheaves}\label{bicomplete} Assume moreover that $\scc$ is a bicomplete $\scc$-category: $\scc$ is bicomplete in the usual set-based sense and the tensors and cotensors: $$ c\otimes W,\quad [W,c], \quad c, W\in\scc, $$ satisfy the $\scc$-adjunctions $$ \uHom_{\scc}(c_1\otimes W,c_2)\simeq [W,\uHom_{\scc}(c_1,c_2)]\simeq \uHom_{\scc}(c_1,[W,c_2]). $$ (Here $[-,-]=\uHom_{\scc}(-,-)$ but below we will need to separate these two operations.) {\it This will be our standard assumption on $\scc$ from now on}. The category $\underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)_0$ is the underlying category of the $\scc$-category $\underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)$, where the $\Hom$-object in $\underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)$ is defined as the enriched end:  egin{equation}\label{kol12} \uHom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)=\int_{Y\in {m Perf}_S}\uHom_{\scc}( \sff(Y),\sg(Y)) \end{equation} computed as an ordinary limit in $\scc$. More precisely, it is the equalizer in $\scc$ given by the diagram $$ \xymatrix{ \prod_{Y\in {m Perf}_S}\uHom_{\scc}(\sff(Y),\sg(Y))\ar@<-1mm>[r] \ar@<1mm>[r] & \prod_{Y,Y_1\in {m Perf}_S}\uHom_{\scc}(\uHom_S(Y_1,Y)\otimes\sff(Y),\sg(Y_1)), } $$ where the parallel arrows are defined via the evaluation maps $$ \uHom_S(Y_1,Y)\otimes\sff(Y) 	o \sff(Y_1),\quad \uHom_S(Y_1,Y)\otimes\sg(Y)	o \sg(Y_1) $$ of the $\scc$-presheaves $ \sff, \sg$. We have $\uHom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)(*)=\Hom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)$. The category $\underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)$ is a bicomplete $\scc$-category \cite[Sec. 3.3]{Kelly} with limits and colimits computed objectwise. Hence it is tensored and cotensored over $\scc$: we have the tensor functor  egin{align*} (-)\otimes (-):\quad & \scc	imes \underline{m PSh}(S,\scc)	o \underline{m PSh}(S,\scc),\ & W\otimes\sff=\{Y\mapsto W\otimes\sff(Y)\}, \end{align*} and the cotensor functor  egin{align*} [-,-]:\quad & \scc^{m op}	imes \underline{m PSh}(S,\scc)	o \underline{m PSh}(S,\scc),\ & [W,\sff]=\{Y\mapsto \uHom_{\scc}(W,\sff(Y))\}, \end{align*} such that, for each $W\in \scc$, there is a natural isomorphim  egin{equation}\label{mor10} \uHom_{\scc}(W,\uHom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg))\simeq \uHom_{\scc}(\sff,[W,\sg]). \end{equation} Moreover, for each $W\in \scc$, there is a natural isomorphim $$ \uHom_{\scc}(W\otimes\sff,\sg)\simeq\uHom_{\scc}(W,\uHom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)). $$  egin{remark}{m (Topological presheaves)} \label{koczkodan1} The presheaves studied in Section ef{naive1}, which we called "{topological presheaves}", also form a $\scc$-category. We will call such $\scc$-categories $ {m PSh}(S,\scc)$. Their underlying categories ootnote{For an enriched category $\sa$, we denote by $\sa_0$ the underlying category.} ${m PSh}(S,\scc)_0$ are defined as in Section ef{warsz1} but with the trivial enrichment on the mapping spaces, i.e., in the structure maps \eqref{str2}, instead of $\uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)$ we take $\underline{\Hom_S(Y_1,Y_2)}$, where $\Hom_S(Y_1,Y_2)$ is given the discrete topology. Hence they are canonically induced by structure maps of the form  egin{equation}\label{str1} \sff_{Y_1, Y_2}:\quad \Hom_S(Y_1,Y_2)	o \Hom_{\scc}(\sff(Y_2),\sff(Y_1)). \end{equation} The $\Hom$-object is defined as in \eqref{kol12}. We have the forgetful functor $$ (-)^{m cl}: \quad \underline{m PSh}(S,\scc)	o {m PSh}(S,\scc) $$ given by evaluating the structure map \eqref{str2} on $*$ to yield the structure map \eqref{str1}. \end{remark} \subsubsection{Alternative description of topologically enriched presheaves} \label{ias2} We keep assuming that the ${m Cond}$-category $\scc$ is bicomplete. In that case the category $\underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)_0$ has an alternative description, which will allow us to understand it better. We want to think of a ${m Cond}$-presheaf $\sff: {m Perf}^{m op}_S	o \scc$ as a function $$ \sff:{m Perf}_S^{m op}\mapsto {m Ob}\scc $$ plus a compatible collection of (structure) maps in $\scc$  egin{equation}\label{alt1} \underline{\sff}_{Y,T}:\quad \sff(Y	imes T)\otimes {T}	o \sff(Y),\quad Y\in{m Perf}_S,\ T\in {m ProFin}. \end{equation} Equivalently, we can use the adjoints of the structure maps \eqref{alt1} $$ \underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y,T}:\quad \sff(Y	imes T)	o [T, \sff(Y)] $$ and the compatibility condition corresponds to commutative diagrams  egin{equation}\label{alt1b} \xymatrix{ \sff(Y	imes T)\ar[r]^{\underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y,T}} \ar[d]^{(f	imes g)^*}& [T, \sff(Y)]\ar[d]^{(g^*,f^*)} \ \sff(Y_1	imes T_1)\ar[r]^{\underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y,T} }& [T_1, \sff(Y_1)], } \end{equation} for all maps $f: Y_1	o Y, g: T_1	o T$, together with a composition rule. A ${m Cond}$-natural transformation $f:\sff	o\sg$ between two such functions $\sff$, $\sg$ is given by maps in $\scc$ $$ f_Y: \sff(Y)	o \sg(Y),\quad Y\in {m Perf}_S, $$ which are compatible with the structure maps \eqref{alt1}. We will write $\Hom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)_0$ for the set of ${m Cond}$-natural transformations. We will call the category of such data $\underline{{m PSh}}^{\prime}(S,\scc)_0$. We obtain the ${m Cond}$-category $\underline{{m PSh}}^{\prime}(S,\scc)$ (whose underlying category is $\underline{{m PSh}}^{\prime}(S,\scc)_0$) by enriching in ${m Cond}$ the $\Hom$-sets $\Hom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)_0$: $$\Hom_{\scc}(\sff, \sg):=\{T\mapsto \Hom_{\scc}(\sff\otimes {T},\sg)_0\},\quad \sff, \sg\in \underline{{m PSh}}^{\prime}(S,\scc)_0. $$ (We note that $\sff\otimes {T}\in \underline{{m PSh}}^{\prime}(S,\scc)_0$). We clearly have $\Hom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)(*)=\Hom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)_0$.  egin{lemma} The ${m Cond}$-categories $\underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)$ and $\underline{{m PSh}}^{\prime}(S,\scc)$ are equivalent. \end{lemma}  egin{proof} We start with defining a ${m Cond}$-functor $$F: \underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)	o \underline{{m PSh}}^{\prime}(S,\scc),$$ which we will show later to be an equivalence. Let $\sff\in \underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)$. We define $F(\sff)$ as being given by the same function on ${m Perf}^{m op}_S$ as $\sff$. To define the structure maps $\underline{\sff}_{Y, T}$ for $F(\sff)$, we start with the structure maps for $\sff$ $$ \underline{\sff}_{Y, Y_1}: \uHom_S(Y,Y_1)	o \Hom_{\scc}(\sff(Y_1),\sff(Y)). $$ Evaluated at $T\in {m ProFin}$, they yield a compatible collection (indexed by $T$) of maps of sets $$ \underline{\sff}_{Y,Y_1,T}: \Hom_S(Y	imes T, Y_1)	o \Hom_{\scc}(\sff(Y_1)\otimes {T},\sff(Y)). $$ Setting $Y_1=Y	imes T$ in the above and taking the image of the identity by the map $\underline{\sff}_{Y,Y_1,T}$, we get a compatible, in $Y$ and $T$, family of maps in $\scc$ $$ \sff(Y	imes T)\otimes {T}	o \sff(Y), $$ as wanted. This defines a function $$ F: {m Ob}\, \underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)	o {m Ob}\, \underline{{m PSh}}^{\prime}(S,\scc). $$ It remains to define, for each pair $\sff,\sg\in \underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)$, a map $$ F_{\sff,\sg}: \Hom_{\scc}(\sff,\sg)	o \Hom_{\scc}(F(\sff),F(\sg)) $$ compatible with the composition and the identity (see \cite[(1.5), (1.6)]{Kelly}). This amounts to defining, indexed by $T\in {m ProFin}$, a compatible family of maps $$ F_{\sff,\sg}(T): \Hom_{\scc}(\sff\otimes{T},\sg)_0	o \Hom_{\scc}(F(\sff)\otimes{T},F(\sg))_0. $$ But, by the definition of $F(\sff), F(\sg)$, these two sets can be canonically identified. The above proves that the ${m Cond}$-functor $F$ is in fact fully faithful. It remains thus to show that it is essentially surjective on objects. For that we will define the quasi-inverse $G$ to $F$ on objects: $G$ is given by the same function on ${m Perf}^{m op}_S$ as $F$ and to define the structure maps $\underline{\sff}_{Y_1, Y_2}$ for $G(\sff)$: $$ \underline{\sff}_{Y_1, Y_2}: \uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)	o \Hom_{\scc}(G(\sff)(Y_2),G(\sff)(Y_1)) $$ we need to define, a compatible in $T$, family of maps of sets $$ \underline{\sff}_{Y_1, Y_2,T}: \Hom_S(Y_1	imes T,Y_2)	o \Hom_{\scc}(\sff(Y_2)\otimes {T},\sff(Y_1)). $$ To do that, we map a map $f:Y_1	imes T	o Y_2$ to the composition $$ \sff(Y_2)\otimes{T}\lomapr{f\otimes{m Id}}\sff(Y_1	imes T)\otimes{T}\lomapr{\underline{\sff}_{Y_1,T}}\sff(Y_1). $$ It is easy to check that $FG={m Id}$ and $GF={m Id}$, hence $F$ is essentially surjective, as wanted. \end{proof}  egin{example}{m (Rigid topologically enriched presheaves)} We will distinguish a subcategory of topologically enriched presheaves.  egin{definition} A topologically enriched presheaf $\sff\in \underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)$ is called {\em rigid} if the structure maps from \eqref{alt1b} $$ \underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y,T}:\quad \sff(Y	imes T)	o [T, \sff(Y)] $$ are isomorphisms in $\scc$, for all $Y\in {m Perf}_S$, $ T\in {m ProFin}$. Equivalently, if the maps $$ \underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y,T}(*):\quad \sff(Y	imes T, *)	o \sff(Y,T) $$ are isomorphisms of sets, for all $Y\in {m Perf}_S$ and $T\in {m ProFin}$. The full subcategory of rigid presheaves in $ \underline{{m PSh}}(S,\scc)$ will be denoted by $ \underline{{m PSh}}^{m rig}(S,\scc)$. We will denote by $\underline{{m Sh}}^{m rig}(S,\scc)$ its full subcategory of {\em rigid sheaves}: a rigid presheaf $\sff$ is a sheaf if the pro-'etale presheaf $\eta_*\sff$ is a sheaf. \end{definition} We note that the equivalence in the above definition follows from the commutative diagram $$ \xymatrix{ \sff(Y	imes T	imes T_1,*)\ar[rrd]^{\underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y ,T	imes T_1}(*)} \ar[d]_{\underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y	imes T,T_1}(*)} \ \sff(Y	imes T,T_1)\ar@{-->}[rr]^-{\underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y,T}(T_1)} & & \sff(Y,T	imes T_1), } $$ which is just a rewriting of the composition commutative diagram $$ \xymatrix{ \sff(Y	imes T	imes T_1)(*)\ar[rrd]^{\underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y ,T	imes T_1}(*)} \ar[d]_{\underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y	imes T,T_1}(*)} \ [T_1,\sff(Y	imes T)](*)\ar@{-->}[rr]^-{[T_1,\underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y,T}]} & & [T_1,[T,\sff(Y)]](*)=[T_1	imes T,\sff(Y)](*). } $$  egin{lemma}\label{enriched1a} Let $\sff\in {m PSh}(S_{\proeet})$. The topologically enriched presheaf $\pi_*\sff\in \underline{{m PSh}}(S)$ is a rigid sheaf. Moreover, the functor $$ \pi^{m rig}_*:\quad {m Sh}(S_{\proeet})	o \underline{{m Sh}}^{m rig}(S_{\proeet})_0 $$ is an equivalence of categories. \end{lemma}  egin{remark} The above lemma is also valid for the pair ${m Ab}, {m CondAb}$ (in place of the pair ${m Set}, {m Cond}$). With the same proof. \end{remark}  egin{proof} By Lemma ef{enriched1}, the presheaf $\pi_*\sff$ is topologically enriched. To see that it is rigid we need to show that the structure maps  egin{equation}\label{down1} (\underline{\pi_*\sff})^{\prime}_{Y,T}(*):\quad \pi_*\sff(Y	imes T,*)	o \pi_*\sff(Y, T) \end{equation} are isomorphisms of sets. But this is clear since they are isomorphic to the identity maps $$ {m Id}: \sff(Y	imes T)	o \sff(Y	imes T). $$ Moreover, we have $\eta_*\pi_*\sff\simeq \sff$ hence $\pi_*\sff$ is a sheaf. Concerning the second claim of the lemma, let us start with essential surjectivity of the functor $\pi_*$. Take a rigid sheaf $\sff$. We have the structure maps  egin{equation}\label{down2} \underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y,T}(*):\quad \sff(Y	imes T,*)	o \sff(Y,T), \end{equation} of sets satisfying certain compatibilities. In the language of Section ef{naive1a}, they give a natural transformation of topologically enriched presheaves ootnote{The fact that this is a natural transformation follows from the coherence of the structure maps \eqref{down2}.} $$ \pi_*\eta_*\sff	o \sff. $$ Since these maps are isomorphisms by assumption, we get the essential surjectivity. It remains to show that the functor $\pi_*$ is fully faithful. Faithfulness is clear. Let $\sff, \sg\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet})$ and take a map of topologically enriched presheaves $f: \pi_*\sff	o \pi_*\sg$. Define a map $	ilde{f}: \sff	o \sg$ by setting $	ilde{f}_Y=f_Y(*)$. We need to show that that $f=\pi_*	ilde{f}$. But this can be seen, after unwiding the definitions, from the following commutative diagram (for all $Y\in {m Perf}_S, T\in {m ProFin}$) $$ \xymatrix{ \pi_*\sff(Y,T)\ar[r]^{f_Y(T)} & \pi_*\sff(Y,T)\ \sff(Y	imes T,*)\ar[r]^{f_{Y	imes T}(*)} \ar[u]^{\underline{\sff}^{\prime}_{Y,T}(*)}& \sg(Y	imes T,*)\ar[u]^{\underline{\sg}^{\prime}_{Y,T}(*)} } $$ Here, the vertical maps, after identification of the source and the target, are just identities. \end{proof}  egin{remark} It follows from Lemma ef{enriched1a} that a rigid presheaf $\sff$ is a sheaf if and only if the topological presheaf $\sff^{m cl}$ is a sheaf. \end{remark} \end{example} \subsubsection{Enriched Yoneda Lemma}\label{enrichedyoneda} Recall the following classical construction from \cite[Sec. 2.4]{Kelly}. Let $S\in {m Perf}_C$, $Y\in {m Perf}_S$. We define the functor  egin{align*} {h}^{m top}_Y: {m Perf}_S^{m op}	o {m Cond}, \quad X\mapsto \uHom_S(X,Y). \end{align*} It is easy to check that  egin{equation}\label{Chicago10} h^{m top}_Y\simeq \pi_*h_Y, \end{equation} where $ \pi: S_{\proeet}	o S_{\proeet}^{m top}$ is the canonical projection. In particular, since the pro-'etale site is subcanonical and thus the presheaf $h_Y$ is a sheaf, same is true of $h^{m top}_Y$. Moreover, by Lemma ef{enriched1}, this sheaf is canonically ${m Cond}$-enriched. Let $\sff\in \underline{m PSh}(S)$. The ${m Cond}$-{\em enriched Yoneda Lemma} yields an existence of a $m Cond$-natural isomorphism  egin{align}\label{lato24} \uHom(h^{m top}_Y,\sff)=\int_{Y_1\in{m Perf}_S}\uHom(\uHom_S(Y_1,Y),\sff(Y_1))\stackrel{\sim}{\leftarrow}\sff(Y) \end{align} induced by the maps $$ \phi_Y: \sff(Y)	o \uHom(\uHom_S(Y_1,Y),\sff(Y_1)) $$ obtained, via the adjunction $\Hom(x,\uHom(y,z))\simeq \Hom(y,\uHom(x,z))$, $x,y,z\in {m Cond}$, from the structure maps $$ \underline{\sff}_{Y_1,Y}: \uHom_S(Y_1,Y)	o \uHom(\sff(Y),\sff(Y_1)). $$ The special case of \eqref{lato24} with $\sff=h^{m top}_{Y_1}, Y_1\in{m Perf}_S,$ proves that the functor $h^{m top}_*$ is fully faithful. Moreover, we have $h^{m top}_{Y_1	imes_S Y_2}\simeq h^{m top}_{Y_1}	imes h^{m top}_{Y_2}$. Equivalently, we can formulate an enriched {\em co-Yoneda Lemma} as a ${m Cond}$-natural isomorphism $$ \int^{Y_1\in{m Perf}_S}\uHom_S(Y,Y_1)\otimes\sff(Y_1)\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \sff(Y) $$ induced by the morphisms $$ \uHom_S(Y,Y_1)\otimes\sff(Y_1)	o \sff(Y), $$ which are adjoints to the structure maps $\sff_{Y,Y_1}$. Here $\int^{Y_1\in{m Perf}_S}\uHom_S(Y,Y_1)\otimes\sff(Y_1)$ is the enriched coend: the coequalizer given by the diagram $$ \xymatrix{ \coprod_{Y_1\in{m Perf}_S}\uHom_S(Y,Y_1)\otimes\sff(Y_1)& \coprod_{Y_1,Y_2\in{m Perf}_S} \uHom_S(Y,Y_1)\otimes\uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)\otimes\sff(Y_2), \ar@<-1mm>[l]\ar@<1mm>[l] } $$ where the parallel arrows are induced by the composition and the evaluation maps $$ \uHom_S(Y,Y_1)\otimes \uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)	o \uHom_S(Y,Y_2),\quad \uHom_S(Y_1,Y_2)\otimes \sff(Y_2)	o \sff(Y_1). $$ \subsubsection{Monoidal structures} \label{mon100} Let $S\in {m Perf}_C$ and let $\scc={m Cond}$. We will use the same notation for tensor products and internal $\Hom$'s of ${m Cond}$-presheaves on the category ${m Perf}_S$ as in Section ef{cond-kol1} and Section ef{solid1}. \vskip2mm ($ ullet$) {\em Tensor product.} The tensor products of presheaves are defined objectwise and the structure