eq \alpha_{2,Y} \overline{ eta}$. But, for any non-zero presheaf $\sff\in \underline{m PSh}(S)$, we have natural isomorphisms  egin{align*}\Hom_{S^{m top}}(h^{m top}_Y\otimes W_i,\sff)\simeq \Hom(W_i,\uHom_{S^{m top}}(h^{m top}_Y,\sff))\simeq\Hom(W_i,\sff(Y)); \end{align*} the second one by the enriched Yoneda Lemma. Hence we can find a unique map $ eta : h^{m top}_Y\otimes W_i	o \sff$ corresponding to $\overline{ eta}$. Now $\alpha_{1,Y} \overline{ eta} 
eq \alpha_{2,Y} \overline{ eta}$ implies that $\alpha_1  eta 
eq \alpha_2  eta$, as wanted. \end{proof}  egin{remark} (1) Everything in Section ef{ias1} outside of the definition of rigid sheaves works as well with the category ${m Perf}_C$ replaced by the category ${m sPerf}_C$ of strictly totally disconnected affinoids $S\in {m Perf}_C$. We note that we do have an analog of Lemma ef{enriched1} by restricted the sheaves $\pi_*\sff$ to the category ${m sPerf}_C$. (2) It is possible to define a notion of a topologically enriched sheaf as a finite-products preserving enriched functor. Such objects form a full reflective subcategory of topologically enriched presheaves in the sense of \cite{BAC}, \cite{Ros} (the key point being that the naive sheafification of a topologically enriched presheaf is canonically enriched). In fact in the first draft of this paper we have worked in this setting only later realizing that this does not add anything (besides extra layer of complexity) to the applications we had in mind. It might be however useful in the future. (3) We will call presheaves from ${m PSh}({m Spa}(C),\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})$ {\em Topological Vector Spaces} (${m TVS}$ for short). We will also use this term for the derived category of ${m TVS}$'s (see below) and sometimes, abusively, for the analogous categories with values in condensed Abelian groups, etc. \end{remark} \subsection{Derived version} We study here the $\infty$-derived category of topologically enriched sheaves, show that it admits a canonical ${m Cond}$-enrichment, and compare it with the category of ${m Cond}$-enriched presheaves with values in corresponding $\infty$-derived ${m Cond}$-categories. \subsubsection{Derived categories of topologically enriched presheaves. } We start with the derived categories of topologically enriched presheaves:  egin{align}\label{kaczka21} & \underline{m PSh}(S,{m CondAb})_0, \quad \underline{m PSh}(S,{m Solid})_0,\ & \underline{m PSh}(S,{\underline{\Q}_p})_0, \quad \underline{m PSh}(S,\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})_0.
otag \end{align} These are Grothendieck abelian with compact, projective generators. Hence we have $K$-injective as well as $K$-flat resolutions. This yields derived (internal) $\Hom$'s, derived tensor products, and the (internal) tensor-hom adjunctions in the corresponding derived $\infty$-categories  egin{align*} & \underline{\sd}(S,{m CondAb}), \quad \underline{\sd}(S,{m Solid}),\ & \underline{\sd}(S,{\underline{\Q}_p}), \quad \underline{\sd}(S,\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box}). \end{align*} These categories are defined by taking derived $\infty$-categories of the corresponding $(-)_0$ categories from \eqref{kaczka21} and then canonically enriching them via the global sections of the derived internal $\Hom$'s. The enriched tensor-hom adjunctions are inherited from the internal ones. We have the following result concerning the relationship between constant sheaves and monoidal structures:  egin{lemma} \label{form23-enriched}The enriched analog of Lemma ef{form23} holds. \end{lemma}  egin{proof} Claim (1) of Lemma ef{form23} has the same proof in this setting. For the second claim, we use the enriched end description  egin{align*} \uHom^{\Box}_{S,\Q_p}(\underline{W} ,\sff) & \stackrel{\sim}{	o} \uHom^{\Box}_{S,\Q_p}({W} \otimes_{\Q_{p,\Box}}\underline{\Q}_p,\sff) = \int_{Y\in {m sPerf}_S} \uHom_{\Q_p(Y)}(W\otimes_{\Q_{p,\Box}}\Q_p(Y) ,\sff(Y))\ & \simeq \int_{Y\in {m sPerf}_S} \uHom_{\Q_p}(W ,\sff(Y))\simeq \uHom_{\Q_p}(W ,\int_{Y\in {m sPerf}_S} \sff(Y))\simeq \uHom_{\Q_p} (W,\sff(S)). \end{align*} Here, we wrote $\int_{Y\in {m sPerf}_S} \sff(Y)$ for the equalizer $$ \xymatrix{ \prod_{Y\in {m sPerf}_S}\sff(Y)\ar@<-1mm>[r] \ar@<1mm>[r] & \prod_{Y,Y_1\in {m sPerf}_S}\uHom(\uHom_S(Y_1,Y),\sff(Y_1)) } $$ and the first isomorphism follows from the first claim of the lemma. The third claim of the lemma is the same as the second one and the fourth one follows from the third one. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Condensed vs solid topologically enriched sheaves} The following result is an enriched version of Proposition ef{nyear1a}.  egin{proposition}\label{nyear1b}  egin{enumerate} \item The forgetful functor  egin{equation}\label{form1b} \underline{{m PSh}}(S, {m Solid})	o \underline{{m PSh}}(S,{m CondAb}) \end{equation} is (topologically) fully faithful. The essential image is stable under all limits, colimits, and extensions. Moreover, the inclusion \eqref{form1b} admits a (topological) left adjoint, the solidification functor,  egin{equation} \label{form11b} \underline{{m PSh}}(S,{m CondAb})	o \underline{{m PSh}}(S,{m Solid}): \quad \sff \mapsto \sff^{\Box}, \end{equation} which preserves all colimits and is symmetric monoidal. We have analogous claims for the forgetful functor ${\underline{m PSh}}(S,\Q_{p,\Box}) 	o \underline{{m PSh}}(S^{m top},\Q_p)$. \item The forgetful functor  egin{equation}\label{form2b} \underline{\sd}(S,{m Solid})	o \underline{\sd}(S,{m CondAb}) \end{equation} is (topologically) fully faithful. It preserves all limits and colimits. \item The functor \eqref{form2b} admits a left adjoint $$\sff \mapsto \sff^{\LL_{\Box}}: \underline{\sd}(S,{m CondAb}) 	o \underline{\sd}(S,{m Solid}), $$ which is the (topological) left derived functor of the solidification functor $(-)^{\Box}$. It is symmetric monoidal. We have analogous claims for the forgetful functor $\underline{\sd}(S,\underline{\Q}_{p,\Box})	o \underline{\sd}(S,\underline{\Q}_{p})$. \item For $\sff_1, \sff_2 \in \sd(S,{m Solid})$, the natural map $$\R{\Hhom}^{\Box}_{S}(\sff_1,\sff_2) 	o \R{\Hhom}_{S^{m top}}(\sff_1,\sff_2)$$ is a quasi-isomorphism. We have an analogous claim for the $\underline{\Q}_p$-sheaves. \end{enumerate} \end{proposition}  egin{proof} The proof of Proposition ef{nyear1a} goes through almost verbatim (we just need to replace $h^{\delta}_Y$ with $h^{m top}_Y$) since we have Lemma ef{prodiscrete} (for the second claim). \end{proof} \section{Fully-faithfulness results}\label{lato25S} Topological Vector Spaces are closely related to Vector Spaces as well as perfect complexes on the Fargues-Fontaine curve. In this section we prove two relevant fully-faithfulness results. \subsection{Vector Spaces and Topological Vector Spaces} The algebraic pro-'etale and the topological presheaves are closely related assuming that we enrich the latter. Let $S\in {m sPerf}_C$.  egin{theorem}{m(Enriched fully-faithfulness)} \label{duck1} Let $\sff\in \sd^b(S_{\proeet},{m Ab})$ be such that $\R\pi_*\sff\in \underline{\sd}^b(S,{m CondAb})_0$ and let $\sg\in \sd^+(S_{\proeet},{m Ab})$. The canonical morphism in $\underline{\sd}(S,{m CondAb})$  egin{equation}\label{faith10-1} \R\pi_*\R\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)	o \R\Hhom_{S^{m top}}(\R\pi_*\sff,\R\pi_*\sg) \end{equation} is a quasi-isomorphism. We have analogous claims for $\underline{\Q}_p$-sheaves. \end{theorem}  egin{remark}\label{maybe10} The map \eqref{faith10-1} is constructed in the usual way: By adjointness, it suffices to construct a map $$ \R\pi_*\R\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)\otimes^{\LL}\R\pi_*\sff	o \R\pi_*\sg. $$ For this, we will use the composition $$ \R\pi_*\R\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)\otimes^{\LL}\R\pi_*\sff	o \R\pi_*(\R\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)\otimes^{\LL}\sff)	o\R\pi_*\sg, $$ where the second arrow is $\R\pi_*$ applied to the canonical map $$ \R\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)\otimes^{\LL}\sff	o \sg $$ and the first arrow is the relative cup product defined in the following way. For $\sg_1,\sg_2\in \sd(S_{\proeet}, {m Ab})$, the relative cup product map in $\underline{\sd}(S, {m CondAb})$ $$ \R\pi_*\sg_1\otimes^{\LL}\R\pi_*\sg_2	o \R\pi_*(\sg_1\otimes^{\LL}\sg_2) $$ is induced by the functorial maps in $\sd({m Ab})$, for $Y\in {m sPerf}_S$, profinite set $T$:  egin{equation}\label{maybe40} \R\Gamma_{\proeet}(Y	imes T,\sg_1)\otimes^{\LL}\R\Gamma_{\proeet}(Y	imes T,\sg_2)	o \R\Gamma_{\proeet}(Y	imes T,\sg_1\otimes^{\LL} \sg_2). \end{equation} These maps are compatible with the enriched structure maps as the latter are just induced by the identity maps (see the proof of Lemma ef{enriched1a}). \end{remark} \subsubsection{Proof of Theorem ef{duck1}} We start with a reduction. For $\sff$: we may assume that $\sff$ is represented by a bounded complex, then we can take an injective resolution and truncate it to replace $\sff$ with a bounded complex $\sff^{\prime}$ such that $\R\pi_*\sff^{\prime}\simeq \pi_*\sff^{\prime}$, and, finally, do d'evissage. For $\sg$: we replace $\sg$ by a bounded below complex of injectives, then by a limit argument and a d'evissage pass to a single injective. We end up with needing to show that $$ \R\pi_*\R\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)\stackrel{\sim}{	o }\R\Hhom_{S^{m top}}(\pi_*\sff,\pi_*\sg) $$ for $\sff, \sg\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet}, {m Ab})$ and $\sg$ injective.\vskip2mm { f Step 1.} {\em Passage to presheaves.} We will factor the functor $\pi_*$ in the following way: $$ \pi_*: {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Ab})\lomapr{\epsilon_*}{m Sh}(S^{m std}_{\proeet},{m Ab}) \lomapr{\iota_*}{m PSh}({m sPerf}_S,{m Ab})\lomapr{\pi_*^{m psh}}\underline{{m PSh}}(S,{m CondAb})_0. $$ Here, the site $S^{m std}_{\proeet}$ is the category ${m sPerf}_S$ equipped with the pro-'etale topology. The functor $\epsilon_*$ is an equivalence of categories. The functor $\pi^{m psh}_*$ involves sheafification in the $T$-direction ootnote{This amounts to forcing the additivity property for presheaves on extremally totally disconnected profinite sets and it is easy to see that this sheafification process preserves enrichment.}; it is exact. It is well-defined because, for $Y\in {m sPerf}_S$ and a profinite set $T$, the affinoid perfectoid $Y	imes T$ is strictly totally disconnected. For $\sff, \sg\in {m Sh}(S_{\proeet},{m Ab})$, we have $$ \R\iota_*\R\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \R\Hhom_{S}(\R\iota_*\sff,\R\iota_*\sg). $$ This follows from the adjunction $$ \R\iota_*\R\Hhom_{S}(\iota^*\R\iota_*\sff,\sg)\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \R\Hhom_{S}(\R\iota_*\sff,\R\iota_*\sg) $$ and the fact that $\iota^*\R\iota_*\sff\simeq \sff$. If moreover $\sg$ is injective, since $\iota^*\iota_*\sff\simeq \sff$, similar adjunction yields $$ \R\iota_*\R\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \R\Hhom_{S}(\iota_*\sff,\iota_*\sg). $$ \vskip2mm { f Step 2.} {\em Enriched presheaves fully-faithfulness.} Hence it suffices to show that the natural map  egin{equation*}\label{cieplo1} \R\pi_*^{m psh}\R\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)	o \R\Hhom_{S^{m top}}(\pi^{m psh}_*\sff,\pi^{m psh}_*\sg) \end{equation*} is a quasi-isomorphism for $\sff, \sg\in {m PSh}({m sPerf}_S,{m Ab})$, with $\sg$ an injective sheaf. Or that:  egin{align}\label{zimno11} & \pi^{m psh}_{*}\Hhom_{S}(\sff,\sg)\stackrel{\sim}{	o} \Hhom_{S^{m top}}(\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sff,\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sg),\ & \R^i\Hhom_{S^{m top}}(\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sff,\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sg)=0,\quad i>0.
