^{m top}}(\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sff,\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sg) $$ is concentrated in degree $0$. Or that so are its values on $Y$: $$ \R \uHom_{S^{m top}}(\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sff\otimes^{\LL}\Z[h^{m top}_Y],\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sg). $$ For that, writing $\sff=\colim_i\Z[h_{Z_i}], $ for $Z_i\in {m sPerf}_S$, and then each $\Z[h_{Z_i	imes_S Y}]$ as a colimit of $\Z[h_Z],$ for $ Z\in {m sPerf}_S$, we compute in $\sd({m CondAb})$:  egin{align*} \R \uHom_{S^{m top}}(\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sff \otimes^{\LL}\Z[h^{m top}_Y],\pi_{*}\sg) & \simeq \R\lim_i\R \uHom_{S^{m top}}(\Z[h^{m top}_{Z_i	imes_S Y}],\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sg)\ & \simeq \R\lim_j\R \uHom_{S^{m top}}(\Z[h^{m top}_{Z_j}],\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sg)\simeq \R\lim_j\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sg(Z_j). \end{align*} Here the last quasi-isomorphism follows from the enriched Yoneda Lemma. Evaluating now the above on extremally disconnected $T$, we get  egin{align*} \R\lim_j\pi^{m psh}_{*}\sg(Z_j)(T) & \simeq \R\lim_j\sg(Z_j	imes T) \simeq \R\lim_j\R \Hom_S(\Z[h_{Z_j	imes T}],\sg) \ & \simeq \R \Hom_S(\colim_i\Z[h_{Z_j	imes T}],\sg)\simeq \Hom_S(\colim_i\Z[h_{Z_j	imes T}],\sg). \end{align*} Here we used that $\sg$ is injective. Since, clearly, $\Hom_S(\colim_i\Z[h_{Z_j	imes T}],\sg)$ is concentrated in degree $0$, we are done. The arguments for $\Q_p$-sheaves are analogous using the fact that $\pi^{m psh}_*\underline{\Q}_p[h_Y]^{m psh}\simeq \underline{\Q}_p[h^{m top}_Y]^{m psh}$. \subsubsection{Applications of Theorem ef{duck1}} We list now two applications of Theorem ef{duck1}.  egin{corollary}\label{duck2} Let $\sff,\sg\in \{{\mathbb G}_a, \underline{\Q}_p\}$. Then we have a natural quasi-isomorphism $$ \R\pi_*\R\Hhom_{S,\Q_p}(\sff,\sg)\stackrel{\sim}{	o}\R\Hhom_{S^{m top},\Q_p}(\sff,\sg). $$ \end{corollary}  egin{proof} This follows immediately from Theorem ef{duck1} because both $\sff$ and $\sg$ are $\pi_*$-acyclic. \end{proof} Let $K$ be a complete discrete valuation field of mixed characteristic $(0,p)$ and a perfect residue field. Let $X$ be a smooth partially proper rigid analytic variety over $K$. Let ${\mathbb R}^{m alg}_{\proeet,*}(X_C,\Q_p)$, $*\in\{\emptyset, c\}$, be the Vector Space representing pro-'etale cohomology: $$ S\mapsto \R\Gamma_{\proeet,*}(X_S,\Q_p). $$  egin{corollary}\label{duck3} We have a natural quasi-isomorphism $$ \R\pi_*\R\Hhom_{S,\Q_p}({\mathbb R}^{m alg}_{\proeet,*}(X_C,\Q_p),\Q_p)\stackrel{\sim}{	o}\R\Hhom_{S^{m top},\Q_p}(\R\pi_*{\mathbb R}^{m alg}_{\proeet,*}(X_C,\Q_p(r)),\Q_p). $$ \end{corollary}  egin{proof} Since the geometrized $p$-adic comparison theorems (see \cite{CN4}, \cite{AGN}) imply that $\R\pi_*{\mathbb R}^{m alg}_{\proeet,*}(X_C,\Q_p(r))$ has a finite amplitude, this follows from Theorem ef{duck1}. \end{proof}  egin{remark} (1) Theorem ef{duck1} stays valid (with the same proof) if we take $S\in {m Perf}_C$, $\sff$ -- a bounded complex of sheaves, and replace $\R\pi_*\sff$ with $\pi_*\sff$. (2) Corollary ef{duck2} is the reason why we work with strictly totally disconnected spaces in the definition of ${m TVS}$'s: we need vanishing of pro-'etale cohomology of ${\mathbb G}_a$ and $\underline{\Q}_p$ in nontrivial degrees ootnote{Since the pro-'etale cohomology of ${\mathbb G}_a$ vanishes in degrees~$\geq 1$ on any perfectoid affinoid and the pro-'etale cohomology of $\underline{\Q}_p$ vanishes on sympathetic perfectoids, we could have also used here sympathetic spaces.}. (3) We note however that we can not go "higher", that is, we can not replace strictly totally disconnected spaces $Y$ with w-contractible spaces. This is because in the proof of Theorem ef{duck1} we need that $Y$ remains strictly totally disconnected after base change to $T$ and an analogous permanence property does not hold for w-contractible $Y$. \end{remark} \subsection{Perfect complexes on the Fargues-Fontaine curve and Topological Vector Spaces} Here we will prove a fully-faithfulness result between perfect complexes on the Fargues-Fontaine curve and Topological Vector Spaces. Via Theorem ef{duck1} we will reduce it to an analogous result for Vector Spaces (proved by Ansch"utz-Le Bras in \cite{AnLB}). \subsubsection{Quasi-coherent sheaves on the Fargues-Fontaine curve} Recall the definition of the relative Fargues-Fontaine curve (see \cite[Lecture 12]{SW}). Let $S = {m Spa}(R,R^+)$ be an affinoid perfectoid space over the finite field ${\mathbf F}_p$. Let $$Y_{\FF,S} := {m Spa}(W(R^+),W(R^+)) \setminus V (p[p^{ lat}]) $$ be the relative mixed characteristic punctured unit disc. It is an analytic adic space over $\Q_p$. The Frobenius on $R^+$ induces the Witt vector Frobenius and hence a Frobenius $\phi$ on $Y_{\FF,S}$ with free and totally discontinuous action. The Fargues-Fontaine curve relative to $S$ (and $\Q_p$) is defined as $$X_{\FF,S} := Y_{\FF,S}/\phi^{\Z}. $$ For an interval $I = [s, r]\subset (0,\infty)$ with rational endpoints, we have the open subset $$Y_{\FF,S,I} := \{|\cdot|: |p|^r \leq |[p^{ lat}]| \leq |p|^s\} \subset Y_{\FF,S}. $$ It is a rational open subset of ${m Spa}(W(R^+),W(R^+))$ hence an affinoid space, $$ Y_{\FF,S,I}:={m Spa}(\B_{S,I},\B^+_{S,I}). $$ One can form $X_{\FF,S}$ as the quotient of $Y_{\FF,S,[1,p]}$ via the identification $\phi: Y_{\FF,S,[1,1]}\stackrel{\sim}{	o} Y_{\FF,S,[p,p]}$. Let $Y$ be an analytic adic space over $\Q_p$. We denote by ${m QCoh}(Y )$ the $\infty$-category of (solid) quasi-coherent sheaves on $Y$, and by ${m Nuc}(Y )$ the full $\infty$-subcategory of solid nuclear sheaves on $Y$. For $Y={m Spa}(R,R^+)$ over $\Q_p$, we have ${m QCoh}(Y )\simeq \sd(R^{m an}_{\Box})$, where we wrote $R^{m an}_{\Box}$ for the analytic ring $(R,R^+)_{\Box}$. See \cite{And21} for more properties of the category ${m QCoh}(Y )$. \subsubsection{Topological projection functor} For $S\in {m sPerf}_C$, we have the functor  egin{align}\label{essen1a} & \R\overline{	au}_*: {m QCoh}(X_{\FF,S^{ lat}}) 	o {\sd}(S,\Q_{p,\Box}),\ & \sff\mapsto \{(f_Y: Y	o S)	o \R\Gamma(X_{\FF,Y^{ lat}},{\LL}f^*_Y\sff)\}.
